content:
Updated Default Behavior of Visualforce Section Header Components

The new behavior of the description attribute makes the Visualforce <apex:sectionHeader> component secure by default. Only commonly used, secure HTML elements are evaluated in the description attribute’s output.

Where: This change applies to Lightning Experience, Salesforce Classic (not available in all orgs), and all versions of the Salesforce mobile app in all editions.

How: No action is required to secure Visualforce pages with <apex:sectionHeader> components. Set the corresponding escape attribute to one of three behaviors:

- When set to true, all markup is escaped.
- When set to false, all markup is evaluated (WARNING: makes pages vulnerable to XSS attacks).
- If left unset, only commonly used, secure HTML elements are evaluated.

A new User Interface setting allows you to optionally set the default escape value of all <apex:sectionHeader> components in your org to false. This setting makes pages containing <apex:sectionHeader> vulnerable to XSS attacks and should be kept unselected.

We recommend that Independent Software Vendors explicitly set the escape attribute of any <apex:sectionHeader> components used.

SEE ALSO
Knowledge Article: The Description Attribute of the Visualforce Section Header Component Doesn’t Render Some HTML Elements
Visualforce Developer Guide: Unescaped Output and Formulas in Visualforce Pages
Visualforce Developer Guide: apex:sectionHeader
title: Securing Visualforce Components with Default Escape Behavior
